Keep the structure in ExEff LetRec to ease translation

The shape (letrec f = e) is strictly more general than
(letrec f p = c). Until now the translation from ImpEff to ExEff
translated the latter into the former, which made translation of
ExEff to SkelEff (and Multicore OCaml) impossible. This commit
fixes the problem by requiring ExEff letrecs to have the more
limiting shape (letrec f p = c).

Merge pull request #9 from andrejbauer/master\n\nTctx functions use global context, pattern exhaust only after infer, merged

Tctx now uses Tctx.global by default, pattern exhaustion check only after inference succeeds.

All calls to Tctx.xxx passed !Tctx.global, so I removed the explicit passing of typing contexts.
This means we cannot reason easily in a hypothetical typing context without doing some dirty
work, such as temporarily setting Tctx.global. But this should not create trouble, and the
code is now cleaner.

Pattern exhaustion checking in match statements and checking of irrefutable patterns in
let statements is now done properly after inference succeeds. There might be some uneccesarry
warning regarding the empty type, but this should not create problems in practice.

Types (and type schemes) are now beautified before printing.

Printing does no more funny substitutions when printing parameters, but assumes
that the types (and their parameters) are already beautified. Type.beautify and
Type.beautify2 now return beautified type schemes instead of the beautifying
substitution.

Nicer printing of type arguments.

When a type is applied to multiple arguments, for example (ty1, ty2) name,
the arguments are printed unparenthesised no matter what they are. Before,
they were all printed parenthesised, probably by mistake. Furthermore, I fixed
that there is only one space, not two, after the separating commas. This was
surely a mistake.

Separated types and type definitions.

As it turns out, there are no terms with types Sum, Record, or Effect.
Instead, those terms are of the type Apply (name, ...), where name is
the name of the defined type. The only proper way is of course to separate
types and type definitions.

Type definitions are Sum, Record, Effect and Inline. The first three are
more or less what they were before, while the last one represents type
abbreviations. This separation introduces a few additional functions
(we now need subst_tydef and fresh_tydef), but removes a lot of unused cases in
Type.free_params, Print.type, and Unify.solve. Some of them were already
\assert false"s and others them provided a computation that was never called."
Removed special treatment of the empty type as it is an ordinary sum type.

Rewritten Tctx.infer_... functions.

Functions now call corresponding Tctx.find_... functions and return the
appropriate type (already in the applied form) together with any information
needed for type inference. The documentation is a bit vague, but at least it
is not contradictory to the implementation.

Put Big_int back in.

The switch to int from Big_int did not actually solve any problems. It just made
it look like we could use ocaml = and < where we actually could not, because we
still needed custom comparison functions because of comparison of instances.
So, let us not delete existing functionality in the name of simplification.

Changed optional positions in error messages to mandatory. Added checking of shadowing of labels, fields, and operations.

We really should strive to always equip error messages with positions. This seems to be doable, except for
runtime errors. In fact, in the long run it is going to be almost impossible to always equip runtime errors
with source positions (think of compiled code). Perhaps a good strategy would be to require positions on
syntax and type errors, and to remove positions from runtime errors (and exceptions).

As for shadowing, please note that eff MUST check for shadowing of labels, fields and operations because
it uses them during runtime. Shadowing of any of these breaks type safety.

Code review of pattern exhaustive checking. There are problems.

There are at least two problems:

1. The code assumed all types are inhabited, but this is not the case for the empty type.

2. Exhaustiveness checking is called inside infer.ml, so it can happen quite easily that
pattern warning are issued before type errors. The exhaustiveness code is quite explicit
that it should be called *after* type checking because it assume everything is well typed.

I am inclined to suggest that the inference phase should emit fully typed code, this will be useful in general,
for example when we want to relax the value restriction.

And exhaustiveness checking really has to traverse the code separately from inference, there is no way around that.

Replaced the built-in \standard error" exception instance.

In a similar way that the function ref creates new ref instances, the built-in
function exception creates new exception instances. The only difference is that
an instance created with this function writes out a nicer runtime error when an
uncaught raise escapes to the toplevel.

Along the same lines, I created four exception instances to represent division
by zero, invalid arguments, assertion faults, and failure errors. Beforehand,
they were all triggered by the same instance, only with different arguments.
Now, they behave as usual exceptions and one does not need a special handler to
handle them."

Fixed descriptions of instances.

Each instance now carries an optional description that we use when showing the
instance. Built-in instances are described by \standard I/O", "standard error",
and "random number generation". Instances created with new have no descriptions.
If an instance has a description, we show them as <description>, if not, we show
them as <instance #...>.

Beforehand, each instance already carried a description, but this was never
used, and each instance showed as <instance #...>, even the built-in ones."

Changed how runtime errors such as division by zero are reported.

We used to allow operations to be triggered by resources and we used
this for reporting common errors through the builtin exception instance
err. This trick does not work anymore, so I changed things around.

First I added Error.exc so that err#raise can report an exception.
Then in pervasives I added a type of runtime errors, changed err so
that it accepts runtime errors (rather than strings), and wrote
convenience handlers for handling division by zero and others.

So now division by zero is handled as

  with divisionByZero x with ...

which will evaluate to x if err#raise DivisionByZero happens.
